Overall number of emergency attendances correlated poorly with recorded weather variables and weather warnings (Table 3
). Fractures and fracture related admissions were significantly associated with minimum and maximum air temperature in December 2009–January 2010, although this relationship was not apparent the previous year. Over the entire study period, days for which severe weather warnings for icy roads had been issued were significantly associated with both fracture presentations and admissions. There was a 40% (95% confidence limits 20–52%) increase in fractures on days with weather warnings for icy roads. The results were not explained by any coincidental festive season effects. There was no significant correlation between any weather variable and the number of patients with hip fractures. The relationship between ground temperature, weather warnings, all emergency attendances and fracture attendances at Emergency Departments and Minor Injuries Units are shown in Fig. 1, Fig. 2
.
